<p>In April, The Economist published: "A new generation of Chinese companies is expanding around the world."</p>
<p>Sounds like a familiar topic. But look closer.</p>

<h2>Three Waves of Globalization</h2>
<p>Chinese companies' globalization can be roughly divided into three waves:</p>
<p><strong>Wave 1 (2000s)</strong>: Textiles, home appliances, infrastructure. Representative companies: Haier, Huawei, ZTE. Core advantage: manufacturing capability and price.</p>
<p><strong>Wave 2 (2010s)</strong>: Internet platforms. Representative: TikTok, Shein, Temu. Core advantage: supply chain efficiency and algorithms. The model was "Made in China + Global Operations" — goods produced in China, apps distributed worldwide.</p>
<p><strong>Wave 3 (2025+)</strong>: AI, clean energy, medical technology. What makes this wave different: <strong>they're not competing on price — they're competing on technology standards</strong>.</p>

<h2>What the New Generation Looks Like</h2>
<p>The Economist didn't name many specific companies, but China Daily's follow-up coverage provided clues:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>AI</strong>: Chinese large language model companies are winning contracts in Southeast Asia and the Middle East — not as ChatGPT replacements, but as local-language industry models</li>
  <li><strong>Clean energy</strong>: Energy storage systems are achieving <strong>technology premiums</strong> in German and US markets — not cheaper, but more reliable</li>
  <li><strong>MedTech</strong>: Gene sequencing equipment is opening markets in South America, driven by Chinese automated workflows that cut costs 60% below US competitors</li>
</ul>
<p>The founding teams behind these companies look different too. No longer factory owners and traders — engineers and scientists. They don't say "our price is lower" overseas. They say "our solution fits better."</p>

<h2>A Shift in Three Questions</h2>
<p>David Shambaugh's updated edition of <em>China Goes Global</em> captures this with a simple observation:</p>
<p>In the 2000s, Westerners asked: "What can you make?"<br />
In the 2010s: "What do you want to buy?"<br />
Now: "What can you teach us?"</p>
<p>This shift says more about China's new globalization phase than any data set.</p>

<h2>Implications</h2>
<p>For entrepreneurs going global, two concrete takeaways:</p>
<p><strong>1. Don't copy TikTok's playbook.</strong> Subsidized customer acquisition doesn't work in B2B tech going global. The new wave runs on trust and adaptation time — your product running smoothly for six months at a client site is the real moat.</p>
<p><strong>2. Technology standard globalization requires defining the standard.</strong> Genshin Impact succeeded not because its gameplay was pioneering (open world wasn't invented by miHoYo), but because it defined "cultural hybrid" as a new category. Can your product become synonymous with a category in a niche market?</p>

